// @check
// @error-at 15:9 is `never` (an empty type — `A & B`, an object and a string literal, have no common values), so it has no values
// A `type` alias whose body folds to `never` — here `C = A & B`, an object
// intersected with a disjoint string literal — has NO values: nothing inhabits
// the empty type. The alias declaration is a HARD ERROR at the declaration,
// regardless of use (PR #189), so the `let c: C = { … }` use site below does NOT
// add a second error — exactly ONE diagnostic, NOT a codegen crash (`Unhandled
// AST -> WASM "Never" type`).
//
// The diagnostic RANGE lands on the `A & B` intersection EXPRESSION (the
// `type C = A & B` annotation — 0-indexed `15:9`, where `A` begins), NOT the
// alias name `C` and NOT the `{ a: "x" }` value site, so the squiggle points at
// the impossible type itself (PR #189 review).
type A = { a: string }
type B = "foo"
type C = A & B
let c: C = { a: "x" }
print(c)
